Definition 2.5. A functor $F:{\cal C}\to{\cal D}$ is said to be a morphism of sites $({\cal C},J)\to({\cal D},K)$, where $J$ is a collection of sieves in $\cal C$ and $K$ is a Grothendieck topology on $\cal D$, if it satisfies the following conditions: (i) $F$ sends every $J$-covering family in ${\mathcal{C}}$ into a $K$-covering family in ${\mathcal{D}}$. (ii) Every object $d$ of ${\mathcal{D}}$ admits a $K$-covering family $d_{i}\longrightarrow d\,,\quad i\in I\,,$ by objects $d_{i}$ of ${\mathcal{D}}$ which have morphisms $d_{i}\longrightarrow F(c^{\prime}_{i})$ to the images under $F$ of objects $c^{\prime}_{i}$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$. (iii) For any objects $c_{1},c_{2}$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$ and any pair of morphisms of ${\mathcal{D}}$ $g_{1}:d\longrightarrow F(c_{1})\,,\quad g_{2}:d\longrightarrow F(c_{2})\,,$ there exists a $K$-covering family $g^{\prime}_{i}:d_{i}\longrightarrow d\,,\quad i\in I\,,$ and a family of pairs of morphisms of ${\mathcal{C}}$ $f_{1}^{i}:c^{\prime}_{i}\longrightarrow c_{1}\,,\quad f_{2}^{i}:c^{\prime}_{i}% \to c_{2}\,,\quad i\in I\,,$ and of morphisms of ${\mathcal{D}}$ $h_{i}:d_{i}\longrightarrow F(c^{\prime}_{i})\,,\quad i\in I\,,$ making the following squares commutative: $\xymatrix{d_{i}\ar[r]^{g^{\prime}_{i}}\ar[d]_{h_{i}}&d\ar[d]^{g_{1}}\\ F(c^{\prime}_{i})\ar[r]^{F(f_{1}^{i})}&F(c_{1})}\qquad\qquad\qquad\xymatrix{d_% {i}\ar[r]^{g^{\prime}_{i}}\ar[d]_{h_{i}}&d\ar[d]^{g_{2}}\\ F(c^{\prime}_{i})\ar[r]^{F(f_{2}^{i})}&F(c_{2})}$ (iv) For any pair of arrows $f_{1},f_{2}:c_{1}\rightrightarrows c_{2}$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$ and any arrow of ${\mathcal{D}}$ $g:d\longrightarrow F(c_{1})$ satisfying $F(f_{1})\circ g=F(f_{2})\circ g\,,$ there exist a $K$-covering family $g_{i}:d_{i}\longrightarrow d\,,\quad i\in I\,,$ and a family of morphisms of ${\mathcal{C}}$ $k_{i}:c^{\prime}_{i}\longrightarrow c_{1}\,,\quad i\in I\,,$ satisfying $f_{1}\circ k_{i}=f_{2}\circ k_{i}\,,\quad\forall\,i\in I\,,$ and of morphisms of ${\mathcal{D}}$ $h_{i}:d_{i}\longrightarrow F(c^{\prime}_{i})\,,\quad i\in I\,,$ making the following squares commutative: $\xymatrix{d_{i}\ar[r]^{g_{i}}\ar[d]_{h_{i}}&d\ar[d]^{g}\\ F(c^{\prime}_{i})\ar[r]^{F(k_{i})}&F(c_{1})}$
Definition 1.4. A split extension of magmas is a diagram $\xymatrix{X\ar[r]_{-}{\kappa}&A\ar[r]_{-}{\alpha}\ar@<-1ex>[l]_{-}{\lambda}&B% \ar@<-1ex>[l]_{-}{\beta}}$ in which: (a) $X$, $A$, and $B$ are magmas, $\alpha$, $\beta$, and $\kappa$ are magma homomorphisms, and $\lambda$ preserves zero; (b) the equalities $\lambda\kappa=1,\,\,\alpha\beta=1,$ $\lambda\beta=0,\,\,\alpha\kappa=0,$ $\kappa\lambda+\beta\alpha=1,$ $\lambda(\kappa(x)+\beta(b))=x,$ $\kappa(x)+(\beta(b)+a)=(\kappa(x)+\beta(b))+a,$ $\kappa(x)+(a+\beta(b))=(\kappa(x)+a)+\beta(b),$ $a+(\kappa(x)+\beta(b))=(a+\kappa(x))+\beta(b),$ hold for all $x,x^{\prime}\in X$, $a\in A$ and $b,b^{\prime}\in B$.
Definition 3.1. In the notation above, with $E=(B,X,A,\alpha,\beta,\kappa,\lambda)$ and $F=(D,Y,B,\gamma,\delta,\mu,\nu)$, we will say that the split extensions $F$ and $E$ of compose and call $(F,E)$ a composable pair of split extensions, if the seven-tuple $G=(D,Z,A,\gamma\alpha,\beta\delta,\\ \mu^{\prime},\nu^{\prime})$ is a split extension (of magmas). If it is the case, we shall write $G=FE$ and call $G$ the composite of $F$ and $E$.
Definition 3.5. Let $B$ and $X$ be magmas. An action of $B$ on $X$ will be called firm if $b^{\prime}(bx)=(b^{\prime}+b)x,$ for all $b,\,b^{\prime}\in B$ and $x\in X$. Accordingly, a split extension of magmas will be called firm if its associated action is firm.
Definition 2.1. Let $E=(B,X,A,\alpha,\beta,\kappa,\lambda)$ and $E^{\prime}=(B^{\prime},X^{\prime},A^{\prime},\alpha^{\prime},\beta^{\prime},% \kappa^{\prime},\lambda^{\prime})$ be split extensions of magmas. A morphism $E\to E^{\prime}$ is a diagram morphism formed by magma homomorphisms, that is, is a triple $(f,u,p)$ such that: (a) $f:B\to B^{\prime}$, $u:X\to X^{\prime}$, and $p:A\to A^{\prime}$ are magma homomorphisms; (b) the diagram $\xymatrix@=30pt{X\ar[d]_{u}\ar[r]_{-}{\kappa}&A\ar[r]_{-}{\alpha}\ar@<-1ex>[l]% _{-}{\lambda}\ar[d]_{p}&B\ar@<-1ex>[l]_{-}{\beta}\ar[d]^{f}\\ X^{\prime}\ar[r]_{-}{\kappa^{\prime}}&A^{\prime}\ar[r]_{-}{\alpha^{\prime}}\ar% @<-1ex>[l]_{-}{\lambda^{\prime}}&B^{\prime}\ar@<-1ex>[l]_{-}{\beta^{\prime}}}$ reasonably commutes, in the sense that $p\kappa=\kappa^{\prime}u,\,\,p\beta=\beta^{\prime}f,\,\,\lambda^{\prime}p=u% \lambda,\,\,\alpha^{\prime}p=f\alpha.$ The category whose objects are all split extensions of magmas and morphisms are defined above and composed componentvise will be called the category of split extensions of magmas and denoted by $\mathsf{SplExt}$.
Definition 1.2. For magmas $B$ and $X$ and an action of $B$ on $X$, the semidirect product diagram is the diagram $\xymatrix{X\ar[r]_{-}{\iota_{1}}&X\rtimes B\ar[r]_{-}{\pi_{2}}\ar@<-1ex>[l]_{-% }{\pi_{1}}&B\ar@<-1ex>[l]_{-}{\iota_{2}}}$ in which: (a) $X\rtimes B$ is a magma whose underlying set is $X\times B$ and whose addition is defined by $(x,b)+(x^{\prime},b^{\prime})=(x+bx^{\prime},b+b^{\prime})$ (thus making $(0,0)$ its zero); (b) the maps involved are defined by $\iota_{1}(x)=(x,0)$, $\iota_{2}(b)=(0,b)$, $\pi_{1}(x,b)=x$, and $\pi_{2}(x,b)=b$.
Definition 2.7. Let $h:B\times X\to X$ and $h^{\prime}:B^{\prime}\times X^{\prime}\to X^{\prime}$ be actions of magmas, $B$ on $X$ and $B^{\prime}$ on $X^{\prime}$, respectively. A morphism $(B,X,h)\to(B^{\prime},X^{\prime},h^{\prime})$ is a pair $(f,u)$ such that: (a) $f:B\to B^{\prime}$ and $u:X\to X^{\prime}$ are magma homomorphisms; (b) the diagram $\xymatrix{B\times X\ar[d]_{f\times u}\ar[r]^{-}h&X\ar[d]^{u}\\ B^{\prime}\times X^{\prime}\ar[r]_{-}{h^{\prime}}&X^{\prime}}$ commutes, or, equivalently, in the notation of Lemma 2.3, the equality $(24)$ holds for all $b\in B$ and $x\in X$. The resulting category of actions of magmas will be denoted by $\mathsf{Act}$.
Definition 1.5. Given a split extension $\eqref{split-extension}$, the associated action of $B$ on $X$ is defined by $bx=\lambda(\beta(b)+\kappa(x))$.
Definition 1.1. Let $B$ and $X$ be magmas. A map $B\times X\to X$ written as $(b,x)\mapsto bx$ is said to be an action of $B$ on $X$ if $0x=x,\,\,b0=0,$ for all $x\in X$ and $b\in B$.
Definition 3.9. Let $M$ be an object of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\tt Man$ and $\Lambda\simeq{\mathbb{R}}^{0|\underline{m}}$ an object of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}{\tt GrAlg}\simeq{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}{\tt Pts}^{\!\!% \mathop{\rm~{}op}\nolimits}$. We refer to the set $M(\Lambda):=\textsf{Hom}_{{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{Man}}}\big{(}{% \mathbb{R}}^{0|\underline{m}},M\big{)}\simeq\textsf{Hom}_{{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}% \textnormal{{Alg}}}\big{(}\mathcal{O}(|M|),\Lambda\big{)}$ as the set of $\Lambda$-points of $M$.
Definition B.3. Let $F$ and $G$ be Fréchet spaces and $U\subset F$ be open, and let $\phi:U\rightarrow G$ be a (nonlinear) continuous map. Then the derivative of $\phi$ in the direction of $\mathrm{v}\in F$ at $\mathrm{x}\in U$ is defined as $\textnormal{d}_{\mathrm{x}}\phi(\mathrm{v}):=\lim_{t\rightarrow 0}\frac{\phi(% \mathrm{x}+t\mathrm{v})-\phi(\mathrm{x})}{t}\,$ provided the limit exists. We say that $\phi$ is continuously differentiable, if the limit exists for all $\mathrm{x}\in U$ and $\mathrm{v}\in F$, and if the mapping $\textnormal{d}\phi:U\times F\longrightarrow G$ is (jointly) continuous.
Definition B.9. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a set. A smooth $F$-atlas on $\mathcal{M}$ is a collection of $F$-charts $((U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha}))_{\alpha\in\mathcal{A}}\,$, such that (i) the subsets $U_{\alpha}$ cover the set $\mathcal{M}\,$, (ii) the subsets $\phi_{\alpha}(U_{\alpha}\cap U_{\beta})$ are open in $F\,$, (iii) the transition maps $\phi_{\beta\alpha}:=\phi_{\beta}\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}:\phi_{\alpha}(U_{% \alpha}\cap U_{\beta})\subset F\longrightarrow\phi_{\beta}(U_{\mathchar 28940% \relax}\cap U_{\mathchar 28939\relax})\subset F\;$ are smooth.
Definition 3.28. A functor $\mathcal{F}\in[\hskip-1.5pt[{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{Pts}}^{% \textnormal{op}},\,{\tt A(N)FMan}]\hskip-1.5pt]$ is said to be representable, if there exists a ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-manifold $M\in{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\tt Man$ (which is then unique up to unique isomorphism), such that $M(-)\simeq\mathcal{F}\quad\text{in}\quad[\hskip-1.5pt[{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}% \textnormal{{Pts}}^{\textnormal{op}},\,{\tt A(N)FMan}]\hskip-1.5pt]\;.$
Definition B.11. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a Fréchet manifold, whose model Fréchet space $F$ is a module over a Fréchet algebra $A$. We say that $\mathcal{M}$ is a Fréchet A-manifold, if and only if all transition maps are $A$-linear, i.e., $\textnormal{d}_{\phi_{\mathchar 28939\relax}(f)}\phi_{\beta\alpha}(a\cdot% \mathrm{v})=a\cdot\textnormal{d}_{\phi_{\mathchar 28939\relax}(f)}\phi_{% \mathchar 28940\relax\mathchar 28939\relax}(\mathrm{v})\;,$ for all $f\in U_{\alpha}\>\cap\>U_{\beta}$, $a\in A$, and $\mathrm{v}\in F$.
Definition 3.25. We refer to the faithful functor $\mathcal{S}:{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{Man}}\longrightarrow[\hskip-1.5pt% [{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{Pts}}^{\textnormal{op}},{\tt A(N)FMan}]% \hskip-1.5pt]$ as the Schwarz–Voronov embedding.
Definition B.7. Fix $A\in\textnormal{{FAlg}}$. A Fréchet $A$-module is a Fréchet vector space $F$, together with a continuous action $\displaystyle A\times F$ $\displaystyle\>\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mu}}{{\longrightarrow}}F$ $\displaystyle(a,\mathrm{v})$ $\displaystyle\>\mapsto\mu(a,\mathrm{v})\;,$ which we will write as $\mu(a,\mathrm{v}):=a\cdot\mathrm{v}$ (and which is of course compatible with the multiplication in $A$).
Definition 3.1. A ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-point is a ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-manifold ${\mathbb{R}}^{0|\underline{m}}$ with vanishing ordinary dimension. We denote by ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\tt Pts$ the full subcategory of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\tt Man$, whose collection of objects is the (countable) set of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-points.
Definition A.1 ([36], page 127). Let C be a category. A set $S=\left\{S_{i}\in\textnormal{Ob}(\textnormal{{C}}):i\in I\right\}$, where $I$ is any index set, is said to be a generating set of $\textnormal{{C}}\,,$ if, for any pair of distinct $\tt C$-morphisms $\phi,\psi:A\longrightarrow B\;,$ i.e., $\phi\neq\psi$, there exists some $i\in I$ and a $\tt C$-morphism $s:S_{i}\longrightarrow A\;,$ such that the compositions $S_{i}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle s}}{{\longrightarrow}}A\mathrel{\mathop{% \rightrightarrows}^{\phi}_{\psi}}B\;,$ are distinct, i.e., $\phi\circ s\neq\psi\circ s$. In this case, we say that the object $S_{i}$ separates the morphisms $\phi$ and $\psi$, and that the set $S$ generates the category C.
Definition 2.1. A locally ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-ringed space, $n\in\mathbb{N}$, is a pair $X:=(|X|,\mathcal{O}_{X})$, where $|X|$ is a second-countable Hausdorff space, and a $\mathcal{O}_{X}$ is a sheaf of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-graded ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-commutative associative unital $\mathbb{R}$-algebras, such that the stalks $\mathcal{O}_{p}$, $p\in|X|$, are local rings.
Definition B.1. A Fréchet (vector) space is a complete Hausdorff metrizable locally convex topological vectorspace.
Definition 2.3. A ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-Grassmann algebra $\Lambda^{\,\underline{q}}:={\mathbb{R}}[[\mathchar 28952\relax]]$ is the ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-graded ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-commutative associative unital ${\mathbb{R}}$-algebra of all formal power series with coefficients in ${\mathbb{R}}$ generated by homogeneous parameters $\mathchar 28952\relax^{\alpha}$ subject to the commutation relation $\mathchar 28952\relax^{\alpha}\mathchar 28952\relax^{\beta}=(-1)^{\langle% \underline{\alpha},\underline{\beta}\rangle}\mathchar 28952\relax^{\beta}% \mathchar 28952\relax^{\alpha},$ where $\underline{\mathchar 28939\relax}:=\deg(\mathchar 28952\relax^{\alpha})\in{% \mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\setminus\underline{0}$, $\underline{0}=(0,\ldots,0)$. The tuple $\underline{q}=(q_{1},q_{2},\cdots,q_{N})$, $N=2^{n}-1$, provides the number $q_{i}$ of generators $\mathchar 28952\relax^{\mathchar 28939\relax}$, which have the $i$-th degree in ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\setminus\underline{0}$ (endowed with its standard order). A morphism of $\,{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-Grassmann algebras, $\psi^{*}:\Lambda^{\,\underline{q}}\rightarrow\Lambda^{\,\underline{p}}$, is a map of ${\mathbb{R}}$-algebras that preserves the ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-grading and the units. We denote the category of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-Grassmann algebras and corresponding morphisms by ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{GrAlg}}$.
Definition B.8. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a set. An $F$-chart of $\mathcal{M}$ is a bijective map $\phi:U\to\phi(U)\subset F$, where $U\subset\mathcal{M}$ and $\phi(U)$ is an open subset of a Fréchet space $F$.
Definition 2.7. A (smooth) ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-manifold of dimension $p|\underline{q}$ is a locally ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-ringed space $M:=\left(|M|,\mathcal{O}_{M}\right)$, which is locally isomorphic to the locally ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-ringed space $\mathbb{R}^{p|\underline{q}}:=\left(\mathbb{R}^{p},C^{\infty}_{\mathbb{R}^{p}}% [[\mathchar 28952\relax]]\right)$. Local sections of $\mathcal{O}_{M}$ are thus formal power series in the ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-graded variables $\mathchar 28952\relax$ with smooth coefficients, $\mathcal{O}_{M}(|U|)\simeq C^{\infty}_{{\mathbb{R}}^{p}}(|U|)[[\mathchar 28952% \relax]]:=\left\{\sum_{\alpha\in\mathbb{N}^{\sum_{i}\!q_{i}}}\mathchar 28952% \relax^{\alpha}f_{\alpha}:f_{\alpha}\in C_{{\mathbb{R}}^{p}}^{\infty}(|U|)% \right\},$ for ‘small enough’ open subsets $|U|\subset|M|$. A ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-morphism, i.e., a morphism between two ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-manifolds, say $M$ and $N$, is a morphism of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-ringed spaces, that is, a pair $\phi=(|\phi|,\phi^{*}):(|M|,\mathcal{O}_{M})\rightarrow(|N|,\mathcal{O}_{N})$ consisting of a continuous map $|\phi|:|M|\rightarrow|N|$ and a sheaf morphism $\phi^{*}:\mathcal{O}_{N}\rightarrow|\mathchar 28958\relax|_{*}\mathcal{O}_{M}$, i.e., a family of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-graded unital ${\mathbb{R}}$-algebra morphisms $\phi^{*}_{|V|}:\mathcal{O}_{N}(|V|)\rightarrow\mathcal{O}_{M}(|\phi|^{-1}(|V|))$ ($|V|\subset|N|$ open), which commute with restrictions. We will refer to the global sections of the structure sheaf $\mathcal{O}_{M}$ as functions on $M$ and denote them as $C^{\infty}(M):=\mathcal{O}_{M}(|M|)$.
Definition 2.10. A (smooth) ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-manifold of dimension $p|\underline{q}$ is a (second-countable Hausdorff) smooth manifold $|M|$ together with a preferred $p|\underline{q}$-atlas over it.
Definition 3.23. The category $[\hskip-1.5pt[{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{Pts}}^{\textnormal{op}},{\tt A(% N)FMan}]\hskip-1.5pt]$ is the subcategory of the category $[{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{Pts}}^{\textnormal{op}},{\tt A(N)FMan}]$, (i) whose objects are the functors $\mathcal{F}$, such that, for any $\mathchar 28675\relax\in{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}{\tt Pts}^{\!\!\mathop{\rm~{}op}\nolimits}$, the value $\mathcal{F}(\mathchar 28675\relax)$ is a (nuclear) Fréchet $\mathchar 28675\relax_{0}$-manifold, and (ii) whose morphisms are natural transformations $\mathchar 28945\relax:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$, such that, for any $\mathchar 28675\relax$, the component $\mathchar 28945\relax_{\Lambda}:\mathcal{F}(\Lambda)\to\mathcal{G}(\Lambda)$ is $\Lambda_{0}$-smooth.
Definition B.5. A Fréchet algebra is a Fréchet vector space $A$, which is equipped with an associative bilinear and (jointly) continuous multiplication $\cdot:A\times A\to A\,$. If $(p_{i})_{i\in I}$ is a family of semi-norms that induces the topology on $A$, (joint) continuity is equivalent to the existence, for any $i\in I$, of $j\in I$, $k\in I$, and $C>0$, such that $p_{i}(x\cdot y)\leq C\,p_{j}(x)\,p_{k}(y),\;\forall x,y\in A\;.$ We can always consider an equivalent increasing countable family of semi-norms $(||-||_{n})_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$. The preceding condition then requires that, for any $n\in\mathbb{N}$, there is $r\in\mathbb{N}$ $(r\geq n)$ and $C>0$, such that $||x\cdot y||_{n}\leq C\,||x||_{r}\,||y||_{r}\,\;\forall x,y\in A\;.$ In particular, the topology can be induced by a countable family of submultiplicative semi-norms, i.e., by a family $(q_{n})_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$ that satisfies $q_{n}(x\cdot y)\leq q_{n}(x)\,q_{n}(y)\,,\;\forall n\in\mathbb{N},\forall x,y% \in A\;.$
Definition 2.13. A ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-Lie group is a group object in the category of ${\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}$-manifolds.
Definition B.10. A smooth $F$-structure on a set $\mathcal{M}$ is a choice of an equivalence class of smooth $F$-atlases on $\mathcal{M}$. We say that $\mathcal{M}$ is a Fréchet manifold modelled on the Fréchet space $F$, if $\mathcal{M}$ comes equipped with a smooth $F$-structure. If the model vector space $F$ is nuclear, we speak of a nuclear Fréchet manifold.
Definition 3.29. For any functor $\mathcal{F}\in[\hskip-1.5pt[{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{Pts}}^{% \textnormal{op}},\,{\tt A(N)FMan}]\hskip-1.5pt]$ and any open subset $|U|\subset\mathcal{F}({\mathbb{R}})$, the restriction of $\mathcal{F}$ to $|U|$ is the functor $\mathcal{F}|_{|U|}\in[\hskip-1.5pt[{\mathbb{Z}}_{2}^{n}\textnormal{{Pts}}^{% \textnormal{op}},\,{\tt A(N)FMan}]\hskip-1.5pt]\;$ that is defined by Equations (3.35) and (3.36).
Definition 2.5. A section of $\pi$ is a right-inverse of $\pi$, i.e., a function $\alpha\colon\Gamma\to\Lambda$ such that $\pi\circ\alpha=\operatorname{id}_{\Gamma}$. We consider the set of sections of $\pi$ as an $R$-bimodule under pointwise addition and product by $R$. Given an open subset $V\subseteq\Gamma$, let $C_{c}(V,\pi)$ be the collection of all sections $\alpha\colon\Gamma\to\Lambda$ such that $\alpha=0$ outside $V$, $\alpha$ is continuous on $V$, and $\operatorname{supp}(\alpha)\cap V$ is compact.
Definition 1.2. An étale semigroupoid is a topological semigroupoid $\mathcal{E}$ such that the source and range maps $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}},\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}\colon\mathcal{E}\to% \mathcal{E}^{(0)}$ are local homeomorphisms and the vertex set $\mathcal{E}^{(0)}$ is locally compact and globally Hausdorff.
Definition 5.18. A bundle congruence $\sim$ on $\pi$ consists of two open rigid congruences $\sim_{\Gamma}$ and $\sim_{\Lambda}$ on $\Gamma$ and $\Lambda$, respectively, such that (i) $\pi$ is a $(\sim_{\Lambda},\sim_{\Gamma})$- morphism, in the sense that if $x\sim_{\Lambda}y$ in $\Lambda$ then $\pi(x)\sim_{\Gamma}\pi(y)$ in $\Gamma$. (ii) The $R$-bimodule structure on the fibers of $\pi$ is respected by $\sim_{\Lambda}$, in the sense that if $x_{1}\sim_{\Lambda}x_{2}$, $y_{1}\sim_{\Lambda}y_{2}$, $\pi(x_{1})=\pi(y_{1})$ and $\pi(x_{2})=\pi(y_{2})$, then $x_{1}+y_{1}\sim_{\Lambda}y_{1}+y_{2}$, and similarly for the left and right actions of $R$. (iii) If $x,y\in\Lambda$ and $\pi(x)\sim_{\Gamma}\pi(y)$, then there exists $y^{\prime}\in\Lambda$ such that $y\sim_{\Lambda}y^{\prime}$ and $\pi(x)=\pi(y^{\prime})$. We shall drop the subscripts and denote either $\sim_{\Lambda}$ or $\sim_{\Gamma}$ simply by $\sim$ whenever no confusion arises.
Definition 1.12. Given a $\land$-preaction $\theta\colon\mathcal{S}\curvearrowright\Lambda$, we abuse notation and also use $\theta$ to denote the action map $\theta\colon\mathcal{S}\ltimes\Lambda\to\Lambda,\quad\theta(s,a)=\theta_{s}(a).$ If $\mathcal{S}$ is a topological inverse semigroupoid and $\Lambda$ is a topological semigroupoid, we say that $\theta$ is continuous or open if the action map is continuous or open, respectively.
Definition 3.2. The naïve crossed product $\mathcal{S}\bigstar A$ induced by a continuous, associative $\land$-preaction $\theta$ of an étale, locally $R$-normal inverse semigroupoid $\mathcal{S}$ on a topological $R$-algebra $A$ is the $R$-algebra generated by all functions $f\colon\mathcal{S}\to A$ such that (i) for all $s\in\mathcal{S}$, $f(s)\in\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{s})$; (ii) There exists an open and Hausdorff subset $V\subseteq\mathcal{S}$ such that $f=0$ outside $V$, and $\operatorname{supp}(f)\cap V$ is compact. As in Lemma 2.9, we may restrict the sets in (ii) to belonging to any basis of $\mathcal{S}$. The $R$-bimodule structure of $\mathcal{S}$ is the pointwise one, whereas the convolution product is given by $(f\ast g)(s)=\sum_{xy=s}(\theta_{y^{*}}(f(x)\theta_{y}(g(y))).$ If $c\colon\mathcal{S}\to G$ is a continuous homomorphism from $\mathcal{S}$ to a discrete semigroupoid $G$, then $S\bigstar A$ is graded, with homogeneous component $(S\bigstar A)_{g}$ the set of function $f\colon\mathcal{S}\to A$ as above which vanish outside of $c^{-1}(g)$.
Definition 1.10. Given a $\land$-preaction $\theta\colon\mathcal{S}\curvearrowright\Lambda$, the semidirect product $\mathcal{S}\ltimes_{\theta}\Lambda$ is the set $\mathcal{S}\ltimes_{\theta}\Lambda\mathrel{\vbox{\hbox{\scriptsize.}\hbox{% \scriptsize.}}}=\bigcup_{s\in\mathcal{S}}\left\{s\right\}\times\operatorname{% dom}(\theta_{s})=\left\{(s,a)\in\mathcal{S}\times\Lambda:a\in\operatorname{dom% }(\theta_{s})\right\}$ with graph structure over $\mathcal{S}^{(0)}\times\Lambda^{(0)}$ given by $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(s,a)=\left(\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(s),% \operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(a)\right)\qquad\text{and}\qquad\operatorname{% \mathfrak{r}}(s,a)=\left(\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(s),\operatorname{% \mathfrak{r}}\left(\theta_{s}(a)\right)\right)$ and product $(s,a)(t,b)=(st,\theta_{t^{*}}(a\theta_{t}(b)))$ whenever $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(s)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(t)$ and $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(a)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(\theta_{t}(b))$.
Definition 5.14. The smash product $A\#G$ is the set of formal sums $\sum_{g\in G}a_{g}\delta_{g}$, where $a_{g}$ belongs to $\sum\left\{A_{h}:\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(h)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(g)\right\}$. The $R$-bimodule structure of $A\#G$ is the entrywise one, and the product is the bilinear and balanced extension of the rule $(a\delta_{g})(b\delta_{h})=\begin{cases}ap_{gh^{-1}}(b)\delta_{h},&\text{if }% \operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(g)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(h)\\ 0,&\text{otherwise.}\end{cases}$
Definition 2.11. Let $G$ be a discrete semigroupoid. An algebra $A$ over a ring $R$ is $G$-graded if it is equipped with a family $\left\{A_{g}\right\}_{g\in G}$ of sub-bimodules satisfying (i) $A=\oplus_{g\in G}A_{g}$; (ii) $A_{g}A_{h}\subseteq A_{gh}$ whenever $(g,h)\in G^{(2)}$; (iii) $A_{g}A_{h}=\left\{0\right\}$ whenever $(g,h)\not\in G^{(2)}$. Each sub-bimodule $A_{g}$ is called a homogeneous component of the graded algebra $A$. A graded homomorphism between two $G$-graded algebras $A=\oplus_{g\in G}A_{g}$ and $B=\oplus_{g\in G}B_{g}$ is an algebra homomorphism $\phi\colon A\to B$ satisfying $\phi(A_{g})\subseteq B_{g}$ for all $g\in G$. If $\phi$ is bijective then it is called a graded isomorphism. (The inverse of any graded isomorphism is also a graded homomorphism.)
Definition 1.5. An inverse semigroupoid is a semigroupoid $\mathcal{S}$ such that for every $s\in\mathcal{S}$, there exists a unique $t\in\mathcal{S}$ such that $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(s)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(t)$, $\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(s)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(t)$, $sts=s$ and $tst=t$. This unique element is denoted $t=s^{*}$ and is called the inverse of $s$.
Definition 2.2. An $R$-bundle consists of a rigid semigroupoid homomorphism $\pi\colon\Lambda\to\Gamma$, together with an $R$-bimodule structure on the fiber $\pi^{-1}(\gamma)$ for each $\gamma\in\Gamma$, such that for every $(\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2})\in\Gamma^{(2)}$, the product map $\mu|_{\pi^{-1}(\gamma_{1})\times\pi^{-1}(\gamma_{2})}\colon\pi^{-1}(\gamma_{1}% )\times\pi^{-1}(\gamma_{2})\to\pi^{-1}(\gamma_{1}\gamma_{2}),\qquad(x,y)% \mapsto xy$ is $R$-balanced; thus it is regarded as an $R$-bimodule homomorphism $\mu_{(\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2})}\colon\pi^{-1}(\gamma_{1})\tensor[_{R}]{\otimes}{% {}_{R}}\pi^{-1}(\gamma_{2})\to\pi^{-1}(\gamma_{1}\gamma_{2})$. We will refer simply to $\pi$ as the $R$-bundle. The zero of $\pi^{-1}(\gamma)$ may be denoted by $0_{\gamma}$ if necessary, or simply $0$. If $\Lambda$ and $\Gamma$ are topological semigroupoids, the $R$-bundle $\pi\colon\Lambda\to\Gamma$ is said to be continuous if (i) $\pi$ is continuous; (ii) The addition $+$ is continuous from $\left\{(x,y)\in\Lambda\times\Lambda:\pi(x)=\pi(y)\right\}$ to $\Lambda$; (iii) Left and right scalar multiplications are continuous (i.e., the map $(r,x)\mapsto(rx,xr)$ from $R\times\Lambda$ to $\Lambda\times\Lambda$ is continuous). (iv) The zero function $\mathbf{0}\colon\Gamma\to\Lambda$, $\gamma\mapsto 0_{\gamma}$ is continuous;
Definition 4.1. Let $X$ and $Y$ be topological spaces and let $\mathcal{A}$ be any collection of functions from $X$ to $Y$. The compact-open topology on $\mathcal{A}$ is the topology generated by sets of the form $[K,V]=\left\{f\in\mathcal{A}:f(K)\subseteq V\right\},$ where $K\subseteq X$ is compact and $V\subseteq Y$ is open. Note that these sets form a sub-basis for the compact-open topology, and not a basis.
Definition 1.6. An ideal of a semigroupoid $\Lambda$ is a subset $I\subseteq\Lambda$ such that $I\Lambda\cup\Lambda I\subseteq I$.
Definition 2.4. Let $R$ be a unital topological ring. A topological space $X$ is said to be $R$-normal if for any two disjoint closed subsets $A,B\subseteq X$ there exists a continuous function $f\colon X\to R$ such that $f=0$ on $A$ and $f=1$ on $B$. The space $X$ is said to be locally $R$-normal if every point of $X$ admits a basis of $R$-normal neighbourhoods.
Definition 1.1. A semigroupoid consists of a tuple $(\Lambda,\Lambda^{(0)},\Lambda^{(2)},\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}},\operatorname% {\mathfrak{r}},\mu)$, where (i) $\Lambda$ is a directed graph (or quiver) over $\Lambda^{(0)}$, with source and range maps $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}},\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}\colon\Lambda\to\Lambda% ^{(0)}$, respectively; (we allow loops and multiple arrows between vertices) (ii) $\Lambda^{(2)}=\left\{(a,b)\in\Lambda\times\Lambda:\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(% a)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(b)\right\}$ is the set of composable pairs. Note that this is also the graph of $2$-paths on $\Lambda$; (iii) $\mu\colon\Lambda^{(2)}\to\Lambda$ is the multiplication or product map, and denoted by concatenation – $\mu(a,b)=ab$; (iv) $\mu$ is a graph morphism from $\Lambda^{(2)}$ to $\Lambda$, i.e., if $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(a)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(b)$ then $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(ab)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(b)$ and $\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(ab)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(a)$; (v) $\mu$ is associative, i.e., $(ab)c=a(bc)$ whenever $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(a)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(b)$ and $\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(b)=\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(c)$.
Definition 1.11. A $\land$-preaction $\theta\colon\mathcal{S}\curvearrowright\Lambda$ is associative if for all $s,t,u\in\mathcal{S}$ with $stu$ defined, and all $(a,b,c)\in\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{s})\times\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{t})% \times\operatorname{ran}(\theta_{u})$, we have $\theta_{t^{*}}(a\theta_{t}(b))c=\theta_{t^{*}}(a\theta_{t}(bc))$. This is equivalent to the semidirect product being associative with respect to the product in Definition 1.10 (see the proof of [14, Theorem 2.56]).
Definition 1.4. A bisection of a semigroupoid $\mathcal{E}$ is a subset $U\subseteq\mathcal{E}$ such that the source and range maps are injective on $U$. If $\mathcal{E}$ is étale, we denote by $\mathbf{B}(\mathcal{E})$ the set of all open bisections of $\mathcal{E}$. In this case, $\mathbf{B}(\mathcal{E})$ is a topological basis for $\mathcal{E}$, and it is closed under products of sets (and hence is a semigroup).
Definition 3.1. The naïve crossed product (induced by $\theta$) is the sectional algebra $S\bigstar A\mathrel{\vbox{\hbox{\scriptsize.}\hbox{\scriptsize.}}}=\mathcal{A}% (\pi)$.
Definition 1.7. A $\land$-preaction $\theta$ of an inverse semigroupoid $\mathcal{S}$ on a semigroupoid $\Lambda$ consists of a collection of maps $\left\{\theta_{s}\right\}_{s\in\mathcal{S}}$ satisfying: (i) For all $v\in\mathcal{S}^{(0)}$, $\bigcup_{s\in\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}^{-1}(v)}\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{s})$ is an ideal of $\Lambda$, which we temporarily denote $I(\theta,v)$; (ii) For all $s\in\mathcal{S}$, $\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{s})$ is an ideal of $I(\theta,\operatorname{\mathfrak{s}}(s))$, $\operatorname{ran}(\theta_{s})$ is an ideal of $I(\theta,\operatorname{\mathfrak{r}}(s))$, and $\theta_{s}$ is a semigroupoid isomorphism from $\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{s})$ to $\operatorname{ran}(\theta_{s})$; (iii) For all $s\in\mathcal{S}$, $\theta_{s^{*}}=\theta_{s}^{-1}$ (in particular $\operatorname{ran}(\theta_{s})=\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{s^{*}}))$; (iv) If $(s,t)\in\mathcal{S}^{(2)}$, then $\theta_{st}$ is an extension of $\theta_{s}\theta_{t}$, i.e., $\theta_{t}^{-1}(\operatorname{ran}(\theta_{t})\cap\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{s% }))\subseteq\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{st})$ and $\theta_{s}(\theta_{t}(x))=\theta_{st}(x)$ for all $x\in\theta_{t}^{-1}(\operatorname{ran}(\theta_{t})\cap\operatorname{dom}(% \theta_{s}))$. A $\land$-preaction is called a partial action if it satisfies, in addition: (v) If $s\leq t$ in $\mathcal{S}$ then $\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{s})\subseteq\operatorname{dom}(\theta_{t})$. Finally, $\theta$ is a global action if $\theta_{st}=\theta_{s}\circ\theta_{t}$ for all $(s,t)\in\mathcal{S}^{(2)}$, or in other words if the set inclusion in item (iv) is actually an equality. Every global action is a partial action. A $\land$-preaction $\theta$ of an inverse semigroupoid $\mathcal{S}$ on a semigroupoid $\Lambda$ will be denoted by “$\theta\colon\mathcal{S}\curvearrowright\Lambda$”.
Definition 5.8. A $\land$-preaction $\theta$ of an étale inverse semigroupoid $\mathcal{S}$ on a continuous $R$-bundle $\pi\colon\Lambda\to\Gamma$ consists of two $\land$-preactions $\theta^{\Gamma}$ and $\theta^{\Lambda}$ of $\mathcal{S}$ on $\Gamma$ and $\Lambda$, respectively, satisfying: (i) for all $s\in\mathcal{S}$, $\pi\circ\theta_{s}^{\Lambda}=\theta_{s}^{\Gamma}\circ\pi$; (ii) $\theta^{\Lambda}$ preserves all of the relevant $R$-bimodule structure, in the sense that if $s\in\mathcal{S}$ and $a\in\operatorname{dom}(\theta^{\Gamma}_{s})$, then $\theta^{\Lambda}_{s}$ restricts to an $R$-bimodule isomorphism from $\pi^{-1}(a)$ onto $\pi^{-1}(\theta^{\Gamma}_{s}(a))$. This in particular means that: (iii) $\operatorname{dom}(\theta^{\Lambda}_{s})=\pi^{-1}(\operatorname{dom}(\theta^{% \Gamma}_{s}))$; (iv) $\pi(\theta^{\Lambda}_{s}(a))=\theta^{\Gamma}_{s}(\pi(a))$, in the sense that either side is defined if and only if the other one is defined, in which case they coincide; (v) $\operatorname{dom}(\theta^{\Lambda}_{s})+\operatorname{dom}(\theta^{\Lambda}_{% s})\subseteq\operatorname{dom}(\theta^{\Lambda}_{s})$. We say that $\theta$ is continuous if both $\theta^{\Gamma}$ and $\theta^{\Lambda}$ are continuous, and similarly for open/associative.
Definition 2.6. The sectional algebra of the continuous $R$-bundle $\pi\colon\Lambda\to\Gamma$ is the $R$-bimodule $\mathcal{A}(\pi)$ generated by the union of $C_{c}(V,\pi)$ for all Hausdorff open subsets $V\subseteq\Gamma$.
Definition 5.21. We say that $\psi\alpha\varphi$ is the section conjugate to $\alpha$ (via $\varphi$ and $\psi$).
